[{"id":"VR038850","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<p class=\"stem_paragraph\">Which of the following best explains why the polymerase from the species <span class=\"formatted_text font_style:italic\">T. aquaticus </span>is often used for <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"P C R\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"P C R\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mrow><mtext>PCR</mtext></mrow></math></span></span>?</p>\n","rubricRef":"VR038850_rubric","features":[{"type":"sharedpassage","html":"<div>\n<div class=\"stimulus_reference\">\n<div class=\"passage\">\n<div class=\"prose style:1\">\n<p class=\"passage_para\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"P C R\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"P C R\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mtext>PCR</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> is a technique used to copy a target <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"D N A\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"D N A\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mtext>DNA</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> sequence. Researchers often use <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"D N A\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"D N A\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mtext>DNA</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> polymerase from <span class=\"formatted_text font_style:italic\">Thermus aquaticus</span>, a bacteria species that lives around hydrothermal vents.</p>\n\n<div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure presents a diagram of a cycle with three stages that flows in a clockwise direction. Beginning at the top of the cycle and moving clockwise, the first stage is Denaturation at 94 through 96 degrees Celsius, which flows into Annealing at 68 degrees Celsius, which flows into Elongation at 72 degrees Celsius, which flows back to Denaturation.\" height=\"225\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/VR038850.g02.png\" width=\"300\" /></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n"}],"choicesHtml":["<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"formatted_text font_style:italic\">T. aquaticus</span> polymerase has an optimal temperature of <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"68 degrees Celsius \"><math alttext=\"68 degrees Celsius \" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mn>68</mn><mi>°</mi><mtext>C</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"formatted_text font_style:italic\">T. aquaticus</span> polymerase does not denature at high temperatures.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"formatted_text font_style:italic\">T. aquaticus</span> polymerase can be used more than once without degrading.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"formatted_text font_style:italic\">T. aquaticus</span> polymerase adds nucleotides to both the <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"3 prime\"><math alttext=\"3 prime\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mrow><mstyle mathvariant=\"normal\"><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>′</mo></mrow></mstyle></mrow></math></span></span> and <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"5 prime\"><math alttext=\"5 prime\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mrow><mn>5</mn><mo>′</mo></mrow></math></span></span> ends of <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"D N A\"><math alttext=\"D N A\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mtext>DNA</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>.</p>"],"answer":1}]